##
##  # ---------- Calibration anchors ----------
##  # DeltaHR diagnostic threshold (Sheldon 2015 HRS consensus): >=30 bpm adult /
##  #   >=40 bpm adolescent within 10 min of standing/tilt, no orthostatic hypotension
##  # Propranolol 20 mg (Raj 2009 Circulation)    : standing HR reduction superior to 80 mg;
##  #   low-dose selectively blunts excess reflex tachycardia without excess fatigue
##  # Midodrine (Sutton/Grubb open-label series)  : standing HR/symptom improvement via
##  #   alpha1 venous/arteriolar constriction, most benefit in neuropathic subtype
##  # Fludrocortisone + salt (small RCTs, mixed)  : modest ~expansion of plasma volume,
##  #   best evidence in hypovolemic-subtype/low-renin patients
##  # Ivabradine (Ruzieh 2017, Moon 2018 case series): HR reduction without BP effect,
##  #   attractive when hypotension limits beta-blocker/midodrine titration
##  # Pyridostigmine (Kanjwal 2011 Cardiol J)     : ganglionic augmentation reduces
##  #   standing HR, GI cramping/diarrhea dose-limiting
##  # Exercise training (Fu 2010/2011 Circulation/Heart Rhythm, "Levine protocol"):
##  #   reverses cardiac atrophy/deconditioning over 3 months, reduces standing HR and
##  #   improves QoL comparably to pharmacotherapy in many patients
##  # Blood/plasma volume deficit (Raj 2005 Circulation): ~10-15% lower than controls
##  #   in a subset, with paradoxically low-normal renin/aldosterone for the deficit
